(c)

Energy of Γ−valleyΓ−valley is about 0.30.3 eVeV lower than L−valleyL−valley. So, when voltage drop across i−collectori−collector exceeds 0.30.3 VV, L−valleyL−valley in sub-collector becomes lower than Γ−valleyΓ−valley in sub−colectorsub−colector. Also, electric field and energy is high enough to promote transfer of electrons to L−valleyL−valley. So, this leads to intervalley transfer of some electrons from Γ−valleyΓ−valley in basebase to L−valleyL−valley in sub−collectorsub−collector. Since effective mass is higher in L−valleyL−valley compared to Γ−valleyΓ−valley, mobility is lower in L−valleyL−valley compared to Γ−valleyΓ−valley. So, electron velocity is lower in L−valleyL−valley compared to Γ−valleyΓ−valley.

So, when collector voltage drop is greater than 0.30.3 VV, electron velocity is lower compared to electron velocity when collector voltage drop is less than 0.30.3 VV.

So, to maintain collector voltage drop below 0.30.3 VV, a p-type dopant sheet is put at i−collectori−collector and sub−collectorsub−collector interface. Dopant sheet accepts electrons from neighbouring sub−collectorsub−collector and becomes a negatively charge sheet. This negatively charge sheet screens the electric field due to the depletion charge in sub−collectorsub−collector. So, electric field in i−collectori−collector is lower in comparision to the electric field in absense of p-type dopant sheet. This means lower collector voltage drop in comparision to the collector voltage drop in absense of p-type dopant sheet. By increasing the dopant sheet charge (by increasing its thickness and doping), collector voltage drop can made less than 0.30.3 VV.

At short times, electrons remain in Γ−valleyΓ−valley with light effective mass and achieve high velocities. However, once they achieve energies comparable to L−valleyL−valley (0.30.3 eVeV), transfer to L−valleyL−valley with higher effective mass takes place accompanied by loss in velocity. At higher times, the high effective mass in L−valleyL−valley prevents transferred electrons from acheiving higher velocities. Also, there are scatterings in and out of the L−valleyL−valley. Due to this intevalley transfer, velocity overshoot occurs in Gallium Arsenide. So, ballistic collector transistors use this p-type dopant sheet to prevent velocity overshoot (due to intervalley transfer) and hence electrons move at velocity greater than saturation velocity. Due to lower scattering, the transport is near ballistic and this is unique to ballisctic collector transsistor. Due to higher electron velocity compared to conventional BJT (absense of p-type dopant sheet) , transit delay is less in comparision to conventional BJT.
